    "Question": {
      "content": "Which of these is wrong about the cardinality n(X) of a set X and its power set P(X)",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "n(X) = 2 if X is a singleton",
        "n(X) = 1 if X is empty", 
        "n[P(X)] = 2^n",
        "n[P(X)] = m²"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "n[P(X)] = m²"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='color: var(--explainColor); background: var(--explainBg); padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid var(--strongColor);'>\n  <h4 style='color: var(--strongColor); margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 15px;'>Power Set Cardinality</h4>\n  \n  <div style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>\n    <strong style='color: var(--strongColor);'>Step 1: Analyze Each Statement</strong><br>\n    • n(X) = 2 if X is singleton: WRONG (singleton has 1 element)<br>\n    • n(X) = 1 if X is empty: WRONG (empty set has 0 elements)<br>\n    • n[P(X)] = 2^n: CORRECT (power set formula)<br>\n    • n[P(X)] = m²: WRONG (incorrect formula)\n  </div>\n\n  <div style='margin-bottom: 12px;'>\n    <strong style='color: var(--strongColor);'>Step 2: Power Set Formula</strong><br>\n    If n(X) = m, then n[P(X)] = 2ᵐ<br>\n    Example: X = {a,b}, m = 2, P(X) = {∅, {a}, {b}, {a,b}} = 4 elements = 2²\n  </div>\n\n  <div style='background: var(--cAnsBg); color: var(--cAns); padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; border-left: 4px solid var(--cAns); margin-top: 15px;'>\n    <strong>✓ Final Answer:</strong> n[P(X)] = m² is wrong\n  </div>\n</div>"
    }
  },
